    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-24T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-24T08:00:00-05:00" n="186"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d186">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/12409: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-24T16:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 24, 1941—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 5:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1198. The British Chargé d’Affaires has informed me that at his request he saw
                    Vyshinski today and in the course of their conversation <pb facs="0187" n="175"
                        xml:id="pg_175"/> remarked that whatever either party might think of the
                        situation<note n="42" xml:id="d186fn42">Germany had started war with the
                        Soviet Union on June 22, 1941.</note> England and the Soviet Union were now
                    associated in a common cause, to which Vyshinski responded somewhat dryly
                    “perhaps.”</p>
                <p>Baggallay also stated to Vyshinski that in view of rumors to the effect that the
                    Soviet Government might find it expedient to remove to some other city in the
                    Soviet Union, he desired to state formally that in such an event the British
                    Embassy would expect to be informed thereof and if necessary provided with
                    adequate railway accommodations to enable it to accompany the Government.
                    Vyshinski stated that he was not aware of the existence of such rumors but
                    stated that of course if the Soviet Government should leave Moscow, [it] would
                    take the action Baggallay had suggested.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
